<article class="consulting-field-note" id="main">
  <!-- LW: the last frame-bender -->
  <header class="consulting-head" aria-labelledby="consulting-title">
    <h1 class="consulting-kicker" id="consulting-title">Open for Business</h1>
  </header>

  <section class="consulting-flow" aria-label="Consulting copy">
    <div class="consulting-block consulting-block--lead" data-label="background">
      <p>I help people and organizations make sense of context, evidence, and competing priorities &ndash; bringing clearer thinking, stronger grounding, and practical direction to complex work. After enough time around the workings of organizations, tools, and human judgment, I&rsquo;ve found myself at a unique Lagrange point<sup class="consulting-sidenote-ref"><a href="#note-lagrange" aria-label="Sidenote 1: Lagrange point">1</a></sup> between disciplines and perspectives. That vantage is what I bring.</p>
      <aside class="consulting-sidenote" id="note-lagrange">
        <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lagrange_point">Lagrange point</a>: a point where competing pulls balance.
      </aside>
    </div>

    <div class="consulting-block" data-label="tools">
      <p>I&rsquo;ve gathered a set of useful tools along the way, and made a few of my own. Most of my consulting tools are for handling <em>knots</em>: places where the grain runs in several directions at once, and the next cut is not obvious.</p>
    </div>

    <section class="consulting-block consulting-arrangement" data-label="arrangement" aria-label="How consulting starts">
      <p>Send me a short or long note about what you&rsquo;re working on. Email or DM is fine. I&rsquo;ll ask follow-up questions to figure out whether I can be useful before either of us puts time or money down. The more context you share, the better we can decide, and the better I can research/prepare if we want to move forward.</p>

      <p>If we both think there&rsquo;s something worth doing, the next step is a paid &ldquo;thought sparring&rdquo; conversation: <span class="consulting-price">$350 for a 60&ndash;90 minute call.</span> I send a few prep questions a day or two ahead. The purpose of the call is to understand the grain of the problem and find the next cut, while giving you a sense of whether you&rsquo;re <a class="consulting-quiet-link" href="https://stephango.com/in-good-hands">in good hands</a>.</p>

      <p>I only book the call if I&rsquo;m confident I can deliver more than $350 in value to you. If I can&rsquo;t, I&rsquo;ll tell you, and where I can, point you to someone who fits better.</p>

      <p>If we want to keep going past the first call, scope and rate are something we agree on in writing.</p>
    </section>
  </section>
</article>
